# Sentinella — Cursor project rules

Sentinella is a mobile-first travel safety and security app for a specific group of
travelers in Italy. It is a Next.js 14 (App Router) PWA deployed on Railway with a
Railway PostgreSQL database. Access to personal features is gated by invite-code
registration; safety-critical content (emergency numbers, guide) is public and works
offline by design.

## Stack
- Next.js 14 App Router + TypeScript (strict), directory: src/
- Tailwind CSS with a custom token system (see tailwind.config.ts)
- Drizzle ORM + node-postgres (pg); schema in src/db/schema.ts; migrations in drizzle/
- Auth: signed JWT (jose, HS256) in an httpOnly cookie; bcryptjs password hashing;
  gate lives in src/middleware.ts
- PWA: public/manifest.json + hand-written public/sw.js (no workbox)

## Commands
- npm run dev            — local dev server
- npm run build          — production build
- npm run typecheck      — tsc --noEmit
- npm run db:generate    — generate SQL migrations from schema changes
- npm run db:migrate     — apply migrations (needs DATABASE_URL)
- npm run db:push        — dev-only schema sync
- npm run db:seed        — seed sample alerts

## Environment
DATABASE_URL, AUTH_SECRET, INVITE_CODES (comma-separated), ADMIN_EMAILS
(comma-separated). Never hardcode or commit these. .env is gitignored.

## Non-negotiable conventions
1. Signal red (`signal` token) is reserved for emergency actions only — if it's red,
   tapping it summons help. Never use it decoratively. Green (`verde`) is the working
   color; `ambra` marks caution.
2. Emergency and guide content lives in src/data/*.ts as typed static data so it is
   bundled and available offline. Do not move it into the database.
3. Never put safety-critical screens (/emergency, /guide) behind auth.
4. Touch targets are at least 44–48px (min-h-[2.75rem] or larger); keep visible
   focus states; respect prefers-reduced-motion.
5. All API input is validated with zod; auth is re-checked inside handlers even when
   middleware already gates the route.
6. When changing src/db/schema.ts, run npm run db:generate and commit the new files
   in drizzle/ — Railway applies them on deploy via npm run start:railway.
7. Any hardcoded phone numbers (embassies, poison control) must keep their
   "verify against official sources" caveat in the UI.
8. UI copy: plain verbs, sentence case, specific instructions. Errors say what
   happened and what to do next.

## Layout language
Signage plates (.plate + CallPlate component) are the signature element — emergency
numbers rendered like Italian road signs with large monospace numerals. Keep new
surfaces consistent with this system rather than introducing new card styles.

## Color system (Core Palette + Semantic Layer)

Core palette — seven hues + a neutral ramp, defined ONLY in
src/app/globals.css :root as RGB triplets and consumed by
tailwind.config.ts as rgb(var()/<alpha-value>). Every hue has the same
five steps: 100 subtle bg · 200 tint · 600 base · 700 strong/pressed ·
900 deep text. Hues: verde (brand), signal (emergency), ambra (warning),
azzurro (info/links), terracotta (warm decorative), glicine
(language/culture), oliva (muted secondary). Neutrals run 0–950;
paper/line/mist/ink are aliases of 50/200/600/950.

Semantic layer — four usage groups, deliberately NOT per-component:
- text: primary / secondary / tertiary / brand / link / on-accent /
  danger / warning / success / info
- fill: page / card / sunken / brand(+strong) / <status>-subtle
- icon: mirrors text, delivered via currentColor as text-icon-*
- border: default / strong / focus

Accent slot — the dynamic mechanism. Components say bg-accent,
bg-accent-subtle, bg-accent-strong, text-accent, text-accent-deep,
text-on-accent, border-accent; a data-accent attribute on any ancestor
binds which hue that means. Bindings: verde (default/brand), azzurro,
terracotta, glicine, oliva. Assigned domains: Guide tabs —
Basics=oliva, Scams=terracotta, Phrases=glicine, Cities=azzurro,
Health=verde; /prepare — Entry rules=azzurro, Global Entry=oliva,
Health=glicine, Setup=terracotta; official-source sections=azzurro;
weather: heat=ambra (warning domain), autumn=azzurro. The .eyebrow
class is accent-aware.

THE RED RULE (unchanged, now encoded): solid signal FILLS are for
emergency actions only — CallPlate, call-112 nudges, the Emergency
tab, check-in "help". Errors and destructive affordances use
text-danger + fill-danger-subtle + border, never a solid red button.
Terracotta is decorative and NEVER means danger/warning; ambra owns
warning.

States: pressed = the -700 step of the bound token; hover only
compiles under @media(hover:hover) (future.hoverOnlyWhenSupported);
focus is one global ring (2px border-focus over a white underlay —
legible on paper, white, and signal); disabled = sunken/neutral tokens,
never opacity hacks; selected = accent-subtle fill + accent text.
Color is never the only signal — every status/category also has its
label or icon.

New UI uses semantic + accent tokens only. A new accent domain rebinds
the slot with data-accent; never invent one-off colors, never write
raw hex in components. Sanctioned hex exceptions: flag/crest artwork,
src/lib/mapStyle.ts (canvas cartography), and the PWA themeColor in
layout.tsx. Dark mode later = swap the :root variables; do not
hardcode around them.
